<subSubSection lastPageId="3" lastPageNumber="24" pageId="2" pageNumber="23" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="2.[151,1127,811,1571]" pageId="2" pageNumber="23">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,315,811,835]" pageId="2" pageNumber="23">Redescription.</emphasis>
Body deltoid in shape; head shorter than pronotum; pronotum arched, sloping posteriad, highest between humeral angles, then descending caudad; dorsum flat; ventral side convex. Body surface slightly shining, covered with coarse dark punctures.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="2.[151,1127,811,1571]" pageId="2" pageNumber="23">
Head (
<figureCitation box="[252,314,907,931]" captionStart="Figs" captionStartId="5.[113,152,1493,1512]" captionTargetBox="[114,1065,227,1462]" captionTargetId="figure-16@5.[114,1065,220,1467]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="Figs. 1-5. Mahea sexualis Distant, 1909. 1 – head, dorsal view; 2 – pronotum, dorsal view; 3 – pronotum, posterior view; 4 – abdomen of male (lectotype), ventral view; 5 – abdomen of female (paralectotype), ventral view." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4476402" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4476402/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="23">Fig. 1</figureCitation>
). Mandibular plates sinuated in front of eyes, apically curved inwards, never spinously produced; clypeus with apex narrowly exposed or completely enclosed (intraspecific variable character). Eyes large, protruding from head outline by most of its width; ocelli situated behind imaginary line through posterior margins of eyes; each ocellus nearer to eye than to each other. Antenniferous tubercles visible from above; antennae 4-segmented (
<figureCitation captionStart="Figs" captionStartId="10.[151,190,1518,1537]" captionTargetBox="[151,1124,361,1478]" captionTargetId="figure-11@10.[151,1124,361,1478]" captionTargetPageId="10" captionText="Figs. 11-16. Mahea distanti sp. nov. 11 – antenna; 12 – pronotum, dorsal view; 13 – pronotum, posterior view; 14 – pleural margin and connexiva, dorsal view; 15 – hind leg (tarsomeres and claws missing); 16 – abdomen, ventral view." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4476412" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4476412/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="23">Fig. 11</figureCitation>
); antennomere 1 (scape) short, not or only very slightly surpassing apex of head; antennomere 2 (pedicel) very long, not subdivided, with erect pubescence; antennomeres 3 and 4 subequal in length, together about as long as antennomere 2, without erect pubescence. Bucculae low, diverging posteriad; maxillary plate tubercle developed; rostrum long, reaching or surpassing metacoxae; first rostral segment not surpassing posterior margin of eyes, hidden between bucculae.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="2.[151,1127,811,1571]" pageId="2" pageNumber="23">
Pronotum trapezoidal (
<figureCitation box="[431,514,1259,1283]" captionStart="Figs" captionStartId="16.[151,190,737,756]" captionTargetBox="[151,1126,220,706]" captionTargetId="figure-268@16.[151,1126,220,706]" captionTargetPageId="16" captionText="Figs. 28-30. Mahea parvula sp. nov. 28 – pronotum, dorsal view; 29 – pronotum, posterior view; 30 – abdomen, ventral view." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4476424" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4476424/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="23">Fig. 28</figureCitation>
); anterior margin more or less slightly concave, anterolateral angles touching posterior margins of eyes; antero-lateral margins rounded, more or less diverging posteriad; humeral angles always very prominent and spinuously produced (
<figureCitation box="[159,224,1355,1379]" captionStart="Figs" captionStartId="5.[113,152,1493,1512]" captionTargetBox="[114,1065,227,1462]" captionTargetId="figure-16@5.[114,1065,220,1467]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="Figs. 1-5. Mahea sexualis Distant, 1909. 1 – head, dorsal view; 2 – pronotum, dorsal view; 3 – pronotum, posterior view; 4 – abdomen of male (lectotype), ventral view; 5 – abdomen of female (paralectotype), ventral view." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4476402" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4476402/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="23">Fig. 2</figureCitation>
); posterior margin skewed posteriad to antero-lateral scutellar angles, margin anterior to scutellum concavely sinuate. Scutellum triangular, longer than clavi. Hemelytra narrow; clavi narrowly triangular (anteriorly with two rows of punctures, posteriorly with one row); corium long, triangular, acutely attenuated posteriorly and reaching middle of membrane, its posterior inner margin concave; suture between corium and membrane brown; membrane large, long oval, slightly brownish infuscated, translucent, slightly surpassing (exceptionally nearly surpassing) apices of postero-lateral angles of abdominal sternum 7 (
<figureCitation box="[955,1034,1547,1571]" captionStart="Figs" captionStartId="5.[113,152,1493,1512]" captionTargetBox="[114,1065,227,1462]" captionTargetId="figure-16@5.[114,1065,220,1467]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="Figs. 1-5. Mahea sexualis Distant, 1909. 1 – head, dorsal view; 2 – pronotum, dorsal view; 3 – pronotum, posterior view; 4 – abdomen of male (lectotype), ventral view; 5 – abdomen of female (paralectotype), ventral view." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4476402" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4476402/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="23">Fig. 14</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="3.[113,1089,223,1047]" pageId="3" pageNumber="24">
Prosternum with deep median groove, flanked by longitudinal, prominently elevated carinae. Mesosternal carina flattened laterally, extending anteriorly between procoxae and reaching posterior margin of prosternal groove, posteriorly reaching between metacoxae. Metathoracic scent gland complex inconspicuous (
<figureCitation box="[566,643,319,343]" captionStart="Figs" captionStartId="5.[113,152,1493,1512]" captionTargetBox="[114,1065,227,1462]" captionTargetId="figure-16@5.[114,1065,220,1467]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="Figs. 1-5. Mahea sexualis Distant, 1909. 1 – head, dorsal view; 2 – pronotum, dorsal view; 3 – pronotum, posterior view; 4 – abdomen of male (lectotype), ventral view; 5 – abdomen of female (paralectotype), ventral view." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4476402" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4476402/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="24">Fig. 31</figureCitation>
); ostiole small, situated laterally between meso- and metacetabula; peritreme horizontal, slightly raised above metapleura, oval, shining; evaporatorium small, narrowly surrounding ostiole and peritreme. Metapleura swollen (
<figureCitation box="[121,198,415,439]" captionStart="Figs" captionStartId="5.[113,152,1493,1512]" captionTargetBox="[114,1065,227,1462]" captionTargetId="figure-16@5.[114,1065,220,1467]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="Figs. 1-5. Mahea sexualis Distant, 1909. 1 – head, dorsal view; 2 – pronotum, dorsal view; 3 – pronotum, posterior view; 4 – abdomen of male (lectotype), ventral view; 5 – abdomen of female (paralectotype), ventral view." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4476402" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4476402/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="24">Fig. 14</figureCitation>
) or not. Legs pale, ochraceous, with short to very short pubescence; femora twice as long as tibiae; tarsi 2-segmented; claws slender, long, straight, apically abruptly rectangularly curved; parempodia and pulvilli developed.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="3.[113,1089,223,1047]" pageId="3" pageNumber="24">
Abdomen with median carina well developed on sterna 
<quantity box="[729,791,511,535]" metricMagnitude="-1" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.143" metricValueMax="1.524" metricValueMin="0.762" pageId="3" pageNumber="24" unit="in" value="4.5" valueMax="6.0" valueMin="3.0">3-6 in</quantity>
males (
<figureCitation box="[872,935,511,535]" captionStart="Figs" captionStartId="5.[113,152,1493,1512]" captionTargetBox="[114,1065,227,1462]" captionTargetId="figure-16@5.[114,1065,220,1467]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="Figs. 1-5. Mahea sexualis Distant, 1909. 1 – head, dorsal view; 2 – pronotum, dorsal view; 3 – pronotum, posterior view; 4 – abdomen of male (lectotype), ventral view; 5 – abdomen of female (paralectotype), ventral view." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4476402" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4476402/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="24">Fig. 4</figureCitation>
) and on sterna 
<quantity box="[113,177,543,567]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="8.89" metricValueMax="10.16" metricValueMin="7.62" pageId="3" pageNumber="24" unit="in" value="3.5" valueMax="4.0" valueMin="3.0">3-4 in</quantity>
females (
<figureCitation box="[281,346,543,567]" captionStart="Figs" captionStartId="5.[113,152,1493,1512]" captionTargetBox="[114,1065,227,1462]" captionTargetId="figure-16@5.[114,1065,220,1467]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="Figs. 1-5. Mahea sexualis Distant, 1909. 1 – head, dorsal view; 2 – pronotum, dorsal view; 3 – pronotum, posterior view; 4 – abdomen of male (lectotype), ventral view; 5 – abdomen of female (paralectotype), ventral view." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4476402" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4476402/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="24">Fig. 5</figureCitation>
), produced anteriad as abdominal spine reaching between metacoxae, resting against mesosternal carina. Connexiva (especially its posterolateral corners) with more or less prominent spines (variable between species and sexes) (
<figureCitation box="[784,961,607,631]" captionStart-0="Figs" captionStart-1="Figs" captionStartId-0="5.[113,152,1493,1512]" captionStartId-1="6.[151,190,654,673]" captionTargetBox-0="[114,1065,227,1462]" captionTargetBox-1="[151,1126,220,628]" captionTargetId-0="figure-16@5.[114,1065,220,1467]" captionTargetId-1="figure-323@6.[151,1126,220,628]" captionTargetPageId-0="5" captionTargetPageId-1="6" captionText-0="Figs. 1-5. Mahea sexualis Distant, 1909. 1 – head, dorsal view; 2 – pronotum, dorsal view; 3 – pronotum, posterior view; 4 – abdomen of male (lectotype), ventral view; 5 – abdomen of female (paralectotype), ventral view." captionText-1="Figs. 6-7. Mahea sexualis Distant, 1909. Pygophore (lectotype). 6 – posterior view; 7 – ventral view. Scale bars 0.5 mm." figureDoi-0="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4476402" figureDoi-1="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4476404" httpUri-0="https://zenodo.org/record/4476402/files/figure.png" httpUri-1="https://zenodo.org/record/4476404/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="24">Figs. 4-5, 14, 16</figureCitation>
); especially postero-lateral angles of sternum 
<quantity box="[470,512,639,663]" metricMagnitude="-1" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.778" pageId="3" pageNumber="24" unit="in" value="7.0">7 in</quantity>
males conspicuously produced; sternum 8 slightly incised posteromedially.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="3.[113,1089,223,1047]" pageId="3" pageNumber="24">
Male genitalia. Pygophore subquadrate (
<figureCitation box="[571,684,703,727]" captionStart-0="Figs" captionStart-1="Figs" captionStartId-0="6.[151,190,654,673]" captionStartId-1="5.[113,152,1493,1512]" captionTargetBox-0="[151,1126,220,628]" captionTargetBox-1="[114,1065,227,1462]" captionTargetId-0="figure-323@6.[151,1126,220,628]" captionTargetId-1="figure-16@5.[114,1065,220,1467]" captionTargetPageId-0="6" captionTargetPageId-1="5" captionText-0="Figs. 6-7. Mahea sexualis Distant, 1909. Pygophore (lectotype). 6 – posterior view; 7 – ventral view. Scale bars 0.5 mm." captionText-1="Figs. 1-5. Mahea sexualis Distant, 1909. 1 – head, dorsal view; 2 – pronotum, dorsal view; 3 – pronotum, posterior view; 4 – abdomen of male (lectotype), ventral view; 5 – abdomen of female (paralectotype), ventral view." figureDoi-0="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4476404" figureDoi-1="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4476402" httpUri-0="https://zenodo.org/record/4476404/files/figure.png" httpUri-1="https://zenodo.org/record/4476402/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="24">Figs. 7, 17</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation box="[695,724,703,727]" captionStart="Figs" captionStartId="14.[151,190,1263,1282]" captionTargetBox="[151,1126,220,1229]" captionTargetId="figure-112@14.[151,1126,220,1229]" captionTargetPageId="14" captionText="Figs. 24-27. Mahea durrelli sp. nov. 24 – pygophore, posterior view; 25 – pygophore, ventral view; 26 – left paramere, ventral view; 27 – aedeagus (basal articulatory apparatus omitted). Scale bars 0.5 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4476422" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4476422/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="24">25</figureCitation>
), more or less dorso-ventrally flattened (
