<figureCitation box="[201,281,863,887]" captionStart="Figs" captionStartId="14.[151,190,1263,1282]" captionTargetBox="[151,1126,220,1229]" captionTargetId="figure-112@14.[151,1126,220,1229]" captionTargetPageId="14" captionText="Figs. 24-27. Mahea durrelli sp. nov. 24 – pygophore, posterior view; 25 – pygophore, ventral view; 26 – left paramere, ventral view; 27 – aedeagus (basal articulatory apparatus omitted). Scale bars 0.5 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4476422" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4476422/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="24">Fig. 27</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="3.[113,1089,223,1047]" pageId="3" pageNumber="24">Sexual dimorphism strongly developed. Body of females behind humeral angles less narrowed; metapleura only slightly swollen; abdomen broader, median carina short, posterior part of abdomen flat; connexival spines with more than one spine per sternum, especially on sterna 5-7; Pendergrast’s organ not developed. Hind femora and tibiae are most probably sexually dimorphic in some/all species; I cannot confirm that given the lack of material.</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="3" pageNumber="24" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="3.[113,1089,1070,1319]" pageId="3" pageNumber="24">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[113,363,1070,1094]" pageId="3" pageNumber="24">Differential diagnosis.</emphasis>
According to 
<bibRefCitation author="KUMAR R." box="[518,674,1070,1094]" pageId="3" pageNumber="24" pagination="1 - 60" refId="ref13645" refString="KUMAR R. 1974: A revision of world Acanthosomatidae (Heteroptera: Pentatomoidea): Keys to and descriptions of subfamilies, tribes and genera, with designation of types. Australian Journal of Zoology, Supplementary Series 34: 1 - 60." type="book chapter" year="1974">KUMAR (1974)</bibRefCitation>
, the presence of both abdominal spine and mesosternal carina places 
<taxonomicName authorityName=": KUMAR" authorityYear="1974" box="[430,503,1102,1126]" class="Insecta" family="Acanthosomatidae" genus="Mahea" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="24" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[430,503,1102,1126]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="24">Mahea</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
as a member of the subfamily 
<taxonomicName box="[820,1021,1102,1126]" class="Insecta" family="Acanthosomatidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="24" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="subFamily" subFamily="Acanthosomatinae">Acanthosomatinae</taxonomicName>
. Within the 
<taxonomicName box="[180,380,1134,1158]" class="Insecta" family="Acanthosomatidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="24" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="subFamily" subFamily="Acanthosomatinae">Acanthosomatinae</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName authorityName=": KUMAR" authorityYear="1974" box="[390,463,1134,1158]" class="Insecta" family="Acanthosomatidae" genus="Mahea" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="24" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[390,463,1134,1158]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="24">Mahea</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Breddin" authorityYear="1903" box="[517,639,1134,1158]" class="Insecta" family="Acanthosomatidae" genus="Catadipson" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="24" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[517,639,1134,1158]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="24">Catadipson</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
are the only genera with 4-segmented antennae. 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Breddin" authorityYear="1903" box="[198,320,1166,1190]" class="Insecta" family="Acanthosomatidae" genus="Catadipson" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="24" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[198,320,1166,1190]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="24">Catadipson</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
differs from 
<taxonomicName authorityName=": KUMAR" authorityYear="1974" box="[465,538,1166,1190]" class="Insecta" family="Acanthosomatidae" genus="Mahea" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="24" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[465,538,1166,1190]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="24">Mahea</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
in the following characters: elongate oval species; head very broad, slightly broader than two thirds of pronotal width; apex of clypeus free; mandibular plates projected as conspicuous apical spines; humeral angles of pronotum not produced, rounded; metathoracic scent gland complex as in 
<figureCitation box="[736,812,1262,1286]" captionStart="Figs" captionStartId="17.[113,152,1206,1225]" captionTargetBox="[113,1088,220,1175]" captionTargetId="figure-16@17.[113,1088,220,1175]" captionTargetPageId="17" captionText="Figs. 31-34. Pleura and metathoracic scent gland opening, most exposed view. 31 – Mahea sexualis Distant, 1909; 32 – Catadipson imernensis (Cachan, 1952); 33 – Noualhieridia rufa Cachan, 1952; 30 – Ibocoris ficivora Roche, 1947." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4476428" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4476428/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="24">Fig. 32</figureCitation>
; connexival margins without apparent spines; head and pronotum with very large black punctures.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="3" pageNumber="24" type="distribution">
<paragraph blockId="3.[113,1088,1341,1398]" pageId="3" pageNumber="24">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[113,258,1341,1365]" pageId="3" pageNumber="24">Distribution.</emphasis>
This genus is known only from 
<collectingCountry box="[604,732,1341,1365]" name="Madagascar" pageId="3" pageNumber="24">Madagascar</collectingCountry>
(four species) and the 
<collectingCountry box="[975,1088,1341,1365]" name="Seychelles" pageId="3" pageNumber="24">Seychelles</collectingCountry>
(Island of Mahé) (one species).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="3" pageNumber="24" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="3.[113,1089,1420,1540]" pageId="3" pageNumber="24">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[113,242,1420,1444]" pageId="3" pageNumber="24">Comments.</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation author="KUMAR R." box="[249,402,1421,1445]" pageId="3" pageNumber="24" pagination="1 - 60" refId="ref13645" refString="KUMAR R. 1974: A revision of world Acanthosomatidae (Heteroptera: Pentatomoidea): Keys to and descriptions of subfamilies, tribes and genera, with designation of types. Australian Journal of Zoology, Supplementary Series 34: 1 - 60." type="book chapter" year="1974">KUMAR (1974)</bibRefCitation>
noticed the resemblance in the descriptions of 
<taxonomicName authorityName=": KUMAR" authorityYear="1974" box="[908,981,1420,1444]" class="Insecta" family="Acanthosomatidae" genus="Mahea" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="24" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[908,981,1420,1444]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="24">Mahea</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Andriai Cachan" authorityYear="1952" class="Insecta" family="Acanthosomatidae" genus="Muschalea" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="24" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="24">Muschalea</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and considered them to be synonymous. He, however, did not examine Cachan’s 
<typeStatus box="[1043,1089,1453,1477]" pageId="3" pageNumber="24">type</typeStatus>
specimens of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Andriai Cachan" authorityYear="1952" box="[265,381,1484,1508]" class="Insecta" family="Acanthosomatidae" genus="Muschalea" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="24" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[265,381,1484,1508]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="24">Muschalea</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. This synonymy is herein confirmed based on the study of 
<typeStatus box="[1043,1089,1485,1509]" pageId="3" pageNumber="24">type</typeStatus>
material.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
